Duck typing is a technique in which the type of an object is determined by its observed behavior rather than by its declared type. In other words, it is a way of determining the type of an object at runtime based on the properties and methods it has, rather than on the type it was declared as. This can be useful in situations where the type of an object is not known at compile-time, or where the type of an object is not important. Duck typing is often used in conjunction with languages that do not have static typing, such as JavaScript, and can be a useful way to improve code readability and maintainability.

In TypeScript, you can use Duck Typing by checking for the presence of specific properties and methods in an object, rather than by checking its declared type. For example, instead of declaring that an object is of a specific class, you can check if it has the properties and methods that you expect it to have.

